Modules

TypeScript supports ES modules for organizing code into separate files with their own scope.

### Exporting

```typescript
// math.ts
export function add(a: number, b: number): number {
  return a + b;
}

export const PI = 3.14159;

export interface MathOperation {
  (a: number, b: number): number;
}

export class Calculator {
  add(a: number, b: number): number {
    return a + b;
  }
}
```

### Default Export

```typescript
// logger.ts
export default function log(message: string): void {
  console.log(message);
}

// Or export default class
export default class Logger {
  log(message: string): void {
    console.log(message);
  }
}
```

### Importing

```typescript
// Named imports
import { add, PI, Calculator } from "./math";

// Default import
import log from "./logger";

// Mixed import
import log, { Calculator } from "./logger";

// Import all as namespace
import * as MathUtils from "./math";
console.log(MathUtils.add(2, 3));

// Import for side effects
import "./polyfills";
```

### Re-exporting

```typescript
export { add, subtract } from "./arithmetic";
export * from "./types";
export { Calculator as Calc } from "./calculator";
```

### Module vs Script

| Aspect | Module | Script |
|--------|--------|--------|
| Scope | File-level | Global |
| export/import | Yes | No |
| Strict mode | Always | Configurable |
| File extension | .ts | .ts |

> **Key Point:** Use ES module syntax (`import`/`export`) for all new TypeScript projects.

codeExample:
// user.ts
export interface User {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
}

export function createUser(name: string, email: string): User {
  return {
    id: Date.now(),
    name,
    email
  };
}

// app.ts
import { User, createUser } from "./user";

const alice = createUser("Alice", "alice@example.com");
console.log(alice);

// Type-only import (avoids runtime import)
import type { User } from "./user";
